CM7Y6-VCiJxp8ot37_5Tr-APdM106WjqebQsL6WD7xf-JObw ). While I encourage you t=
o read the whole thing, I=E2=80=99ll briefly summarize:

* Unity=E2=80=99s per-seat SaaS model worked very well when mobile gaming w=
as a growth industry.
* Unity=E2=80=99s pricing model meant they were well-suited to capturing ne=
w game designers, and could efficiently monetize the long tail without all =
of the complexities necessary for an Unreal Engine-like revenue share.
* Unity=E2=80=99s position in the game creation pipeline meant they were we=
ll-placed to augment their per-seat license revenue with tools that capture=
d a share of in-app purchases and in-app advertising.

The problem for Unity was points one and three: mobile gaming stopped being=
 a growth industry, and the company wasn=E2=80=99t prepared for Apple=E2=80=
=99s App Tracking Transparency changes; it was AppLovin ( https://strateche=
ry.com/2023/an-interview-with-eric-seufert-about-unity-regulation-and-strea=
ming-advertising/?access_token=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZX=
J5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsInR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNz=
cG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJIS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI=
