gYm4w ) that adapted its strategy much more quickly and aggressively and ca=
ptured a large portion of the advertising growth that Unity was hoping for.

That left point two. The problem with a per-seat license fee is that Unity =
didn=E2=80=99t partake in a game=E2=80=99s upside; the allure of a revenue =
share is that it is both cost-effective for a developer to get started, but=
 also the game engine maker can partake in the upside of a popular game. Ag=
ain, though, actually instituting a revenue share is a complex undertaking,=
 requiring agreements, audits, etc.; those are challenges that make sense f=
or a company like Epic that primarily serves other large game companies, bu=
t the complexity is pretty overwhelming when it comes to the long tail.

To that end, Unity saw the opportunity to kill two birds with one stone: by=
 instituting an app-install fee, where the company got paid every time a ga=
me with their engine was installed, Unity participated in a game=E2=80=99s =
upside; if a developer didn=E2=80=99t like it they could get out of the fee=
s by using Unity=E2=80=99s advertising product, which accomplished the same=
 thing in terms of sharing the upside with Unity.

The problem, however, is that this motivation was fundamentally solipsistic=
: while the runtime fees theoretically were a win-win economically, in line=
 with a revenue share, the reality is that there were a ton of immediately =
apparent edge cases that threatened to ruin developer economics; moreover, =
Unity said they would install the changes within months and, crucially, ret=
roactively, even to games built under the old model.

In that Update I suggested a number of changes to Unity=E2=80=99s approach,=
 including pushing out the implementation date, linking it to a new version=
 of the game engine, and not applying it retroactively; the company impleme=
nted most of those changes ( https://blog.unity.com/news/open-letter-on-run=
time-fee ) after a week of intense outcry that, as I noted above, ultimatel=
y drove Riccitiello from the company (particularly since this was hardly th=
e first questionable decision of his tenure). Still, I made the case ( http=
s://stratechery.com/2023/unity-ceo-out-microsoft-owns-activision/?access_to=
ken=3DeyJhbGciOiJSUzI1NiIsImtpZCI6InN0cmF0ZWNoZXJ5LnBhc3Nwb3J0Lm9ubGluZSIsI=
nR5cCI6IkpXVCJ9.eyJhdWQiOiJzdHJhdGVjaGVyeS5wYXNzcG9ydC5vbmxpbmUiLCJhenAiOiJ=
IS0xjUzREd1Nod1AyWURLYmZQV00xIiwiZW50Ijp7InVyaSI6WyJodHRwczovL3N0cmF0ZWNoZX=
J5LmNvbS8yMDIzL3VuaXR5LWNlby1vdXQtbWljcm9zb2Z0LW93bnMtYWN0aXZpc2lvbi8iXX0sI=
mV4cCI6MTcyOTE3MTg1NSwiaWF0IjoxNzI2NTc5ODU1LCJpc3MiOiJodHRwczovL2FwaS5wYXNz=
cG9ydC5vbmxpbmUvb2F1dGgiLCJzY29wZSI6ImZlZWQ6cmVhZCBhcnRpY2xlOnJlYWQgYXNzZXQ=
6cmVhZCBjYXRlZ29yeTpyZWFkIGVudGl0bGVtZW50cyIsInN1YiI6IlJzZXVZRThqZ0hlUHBXSm=
YxZkFiNEMiLCJ1c2UiOiJhY2Nlc3MifQ.ZOYqOgUKR6uctqtHFUoof5jnwcXhbdWBHvjU-9CS5G=
LPxTQ_CcemxYsfJqrnD7_QQAp3FyUbgh2u1mmCdkLq6kv2ZN86JTwt4A6ZQKIabzOXjr5Pl91-D=
YHSfO7nTEthx7g2aMWb2XPxfpD4mlLE6V6XqY2jWtOEnV7m_8WQvDqk4tqpcmjnNsI65FxIlfO_=
6hoHiXHaxqthifO6Ho5V2sE2RFVVvdv_rQoRedQTWMzeQ2NvMFE5UyDzTcnx39Vyl7y3aODCPTp=
mtoVxJppixIpM-yCxpwcse4MHvziRzSV8bQWHks_8FybZItdDYDmMOvm8uX57cuQtvsO9PLVOrQ=
 ) that Riccitiello may have done the company a great service:

There is a case to be made that the last 18 months, and last six weeks in p=
articular, have left Unity far better placed for the future than it was bef=
ore this controversy=E2=80=A6There still remained the overhang of broken de=
veloper trust: sure, most developers probably weren=E2=80=99t going anywher=
e, but there was a lot of bad will after the changes, particularly since th=
ey weren=E2=80=99t completely reverted. Now, though, Unity developers have =
a scalp: the hated CEO is out. Note, though, what remains: Unity owns IronS=
ource, and has implemented its business model change, which unquestionably =
leaves the company better positioned going forward.

I don=E2=80=99t, for the record, want to go so far as to say this entire se=
quence of events was planned; a core piece of my critique of Riccitiello wa=
s that he had big visions but kept screwing up the implementation thanks to=
 a lack of attention to detail. That=E2=80=99s not, needless to say, the so=
rt of executive you would trust with an elaborate conspiracy like the above=
. In this case, though, the results are pretty favorable for Unity=E2=80=99=
s long-term business.

This has obviously been proven wrong, and sitting here today it=E2=80=99s e=
asy to see why: the motivation of a new CEO =E2=80=94 particularly one tryi=
ng to ingratiate himself with a company=E2=80=99s biggest customers =E2=80=
=94 is to throw his predecessor=E2=80=99s most hated policies under the bus=
. And again, even the modified changes were pretty rage-inducing: Unity was=
 basically betting that developers had no good alternatives to its game eng=
ine (Unreal is pretty unwieldy for mobile generally, particularly casual ga=
mes), which it could leverage to force its customers to pay it more and-or =
use its inferior advertising platform.

And yet, all of the initial challenges that drove the runtime fee still exi=
st: mobile isn=E2=80=99t growing, Unity isn=E2=80=99t tied into game upside=
, and the company is losing to AppLovin in advertising. I guess the fact th=
at these big price increases are going to be met with relief is a bit of a =
consolation prize, but while those increases will go straight to the bottom=
 line, they don=E2=80=99t change Unity=E2=80=99s fundamental problems.

Maybe the simple answer is that Unity=E2=80=99s stock is down almost 90% fr=
om its pandemic highs, and over 40% from last year=E2=80=99s announcement; =
that gives a lot more room for gradual improvements instead of business mod=
el overhauls. Even so, the biggest takeaway for me is that Unity appears to=
 be stuck in a flawed business model forever (and, when it comes to Apple=
=E2=80=99s App Store policies, how much value there is in consistency).

Sony PlayStation Pro
--------------------

