When I=E2=80=99m making an extravagant luxury purchase like the PS5 Pro =E2=
=80=94 and let=E2=80=99s be clear, this console is the very definition of a=
 luxury purchase =E2=80=94 I try to answer a simple question: How much will=
 I use it? It=E2=80=99s the same way I justified upgrading to AirPods Pro w=
hen I had perfectly good AirPods 2 already, and when measured against this =
metric the PS5 Pro is worth the cost.

I=E2=80=99m a console gamer (Sorry to all the PCMR readers this statement o=
ffends). And primarily a PS5 player at that. I use my launch PS5 console pr=
etty much every single day. If my console isn=E2=80=99t switched on within =
a 24-hour period, it=E2=80=99s almost certainly because I=E2=80=99m away fr=
om home and physically unable to game. Even then, thanks to the PlayStation=
 Portal, my PS5 often gets used even when I=E2=80=99m in another zip code.

If I purchase a PS5 Pro this November, and we assume the PS6 won=E2=80=99t =
be released before 2027, by the time I=E2=80=99m faced with upgrading again=
, I will have used the PS5 Pro for hundreds, likely thousands, of hours. Ye=
s, paying $699 will sting in the short term, but in the long term, the doll=
ar-per-hour-of-entertainment ratio makes it a reasonable investment.

This hardcore audience is, to be clear, only a portion of the overall PlayS=
tation audience; the reality of a non-growing market, though, is that every=
one is hardcore to a certain degree. Seeking to monetize them is to accept =
and align with the overall bearish trends for the industry; that may be kin=
d of depressing but its a lot more rational =E2=80=94 and ultimately a lot =
lower risk =E2=80=94 than burning tens of billions of dollars like Microsof=
t has trying to fight gravity.

